&lt;p>Suppose we are given a matrix:&lt;/p>
\[
M=
\begin{bmatrix}
4&amp;0\\
3&amp;-5
\end{bmatrix}.
\]&lt;p>At first sight, it is only a rectangular arrangement of four numbers. But the matrix is not merely storing numbers. It represents a &lt;strong>linear transformation&lt;/strong>: it accepts a vector and produces another vector.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>One Word, Many Meanings: Understanding Every Kind of Product in Linear Algebra and Quantum Computing</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/dsblog/understanding-every-kind-of-product-linear-algebra-quantum-computing/</link><pubDate>Sun, 12 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/dsblog/understanding-every-kind-of-product-linear-algebra-quantum-computing/</guid><description>&lt;p>
